cs.CG, cs.DS, cs.DC, cs.DM, cs.NA. 

The paper deals with the problem of computing the Delaunay triangulation, which is a fundamental operation in computational geometry. Therefore, cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is the most likely category. The paper also presents a divide-and-conquer algorithm, which suggests that it could belong to cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing). The algorithm involves partitioning the input point set, which could fall under cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The paper also mentions experiments on synthetic and real-world datasets, which could indicate cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) or cs.NA (Numerical Analysis).
